issues.description: The solution's ExcellenceLand constructor has an extra String parameter named 'name' (public ExcellenceLand(String name, double excellencyLevel, boolean excellentEnough, List<Ride> rides)) that does not correspond to any attribute in the UML/problem statement. The UML and task require ExcellenceLand to have the attributes excellencyLevel (double), excellentEnough (boolean) and a private List<Ride> rides; the constructor should only accept parameters for those attributes in the specified order. The extra unused 'name' parameter is a constructor-parameter mismatch and can confuse students or cause automated tests that check constructor signatures to fail.
issues.suggested_fix: Remove the extraneous 'String name' parameter from the ExcellenceLand constructor in the solution and make the constructor accept only the attributes defined for ExcellenceLand. For example: public ExcellenceLand(double excellencyLevel, boolean excellentEnough, List<Ride> rides) { this.excellencyLevel = excellencyLevel; this.excellentEnough = excellentEnough; this.rides = rides; } Ensure the parameter order matches the attribute order specified by the UML/problem statement.

issues.description: ExcellenceLand constructor in the solution repository does not match the UML and the explicit constructor requirement in the problem statement. The problem statement / UML list ExcellenceLand attributes (excellencyLevel: double, excellentEnough: boolean) and the task text adds a private rides: List<Ride>. The solution's constructor signature begins with an unexpected String name parameter and then takes (double excellencyLevel, boolean excellentEnough, List<Ride> rides). This (1) introduces an identifier ('name') that is not present in the UML/problem statement/template, (2) violates the required parameter ordering (the UML-ordered attributes should be the first parameters), and (3) creates confusion for students about which parameters are required for ExcellenceLand. Students following the problem statement and template will expect a constructor matching the UML (excellencyLevel, excellentEnough, rides) and may be misled by the extra 'name' parameter in the solution.
issues.suggested_fix: Remove the extraneous 'name' parameter from the ExcellenceLand constructor and ensure the constructor parameters follow the UML/task order. For example: public ExcellenceLand(double excellencyLevel, boolean excellentEnough, List<Ride> rides) { ... } (or if the task requires including 'rides' after the UML attributes, ensure the order is exactly: excellencyLevel, excellentEnough, rides). Update template and solution to use this consistent signature so students can directly map the UML to the implemented constructor.
